

Potential Issues
High Priority
1. ~~Email verification is broken in production~~ ✓ RESOLVED — Resend configured with michianapickleball.com, RESEND_API_KEY and EMAIL_FROM set in Vercel, smoke-tested end-to-end.

2. ClaimProfilePrompt: user stuck on screen after creating/claiming a profile
After a successful POST /api/players (or POST /api/players/:id/claim), the component calls router.refresh(). In the (tabs) App Router layout this doesn't reliably re-render the parent server component, so the user stays on the "Set up your player profile" screen and nav taps do nothing.
Fix: replace router.refresh() with router.push('/command') in both handleCreate and handleClaim (components/command/ClaimProfilePrompt.tsx lines 183 and 204).

3. ClaimProfilePrompt: "Find Your Stats" search returns no results
Search hits /api/players/search?unclaimed=true — only returns players where userId IS NULL. Needs investigation: confirm whether the shadow profile for the test user existed and was truly unclaimed, or whether the search filter itself is too strict (e.g. claimed=false vs userId=null mismatch).

4. No rate limiting on API routes
/api/matches (match entry), /api/auth, /api/admin/* — all unprotected. A bad actor could flood match entries or hammer the auth endpoint. Vercel's built-in DDoS protection helps, but there's no app-level throttle.

3. JWT role changes aren't immediate
Auth.js uses JWT-only sessions (no DB sessions). If you change a user's role from user to admin (or revoke admin), the change won't take effect until their JWT expires. Depending on session maxAge, that could be hours or days.

4. Rating ELO is global, not per-tournament
Tournament wins/losses affect the player's global ELO rating. A player who plays a casual tournament will have their global rating changed by those results. Whether this is intentional or a design gap is worth confirming.




Medium Priority
5. Recompute scales linearly with all-time match history
replay.ts replays every match ever, in chronological order, to recompute ratings. Fine at 100 matches; starts to feel it at 10,000+. No incremental recompute exists.

6. connection_limit=1 in DATABASE_URL
This is the Supabase pgbouncer workaround. Under concurrent load (multiple users submitting matches simultaneously), connections queue. For a small group this is fine, but it's a hard ceiling.

7. No match dispute mechanism for players
Regular players can't flag an incorrect match — they have to contact an admin to void it. If the person entering matches (especially in admin mode) makes an error, there's no self-service remedy.

8. Shadow profile name collisions
If two admins enter "John Smith" and "John  Smith" (extra space), two separate shadow profiles are created. The admin merge tool resolves this but it's manual, not preventative.

9. Tournament match list has no upper bound
getTournamentData fetches ALL matches for a tag with no pagination. A tag with 500 matches sends all 500 to the client in one response.




Lower Priority / Design Considerations
10. No draft/recovery on match entry
The multi-step Enter form uses local React state. Navigating away mid-entry loses everything. No draft saved to localStorage or DB.

11. publish/vercel branch is stale
From the git graph, publish/vercel diverged from an older commit (before tasks 9–12). If Vercel is deploying from that branch, the live app is missing the last 4 features. Worth verifying which branch Vercel is tracking.

12. Tag matching is case-sensitive and exact
where: { tag } is an exact Prisma match. "Tag1" vs "tag1" are separate tags. Nothing prevents this at entry time — the admin Tags rename tool fixes it after the fact, but the UX could make this easy to get wrong.

13. No soft-delete for players
Matches have voidedAt. Players don't — a "deleted" player would need to be manually handled. The merge tool is the closest thing.

14. No end-to-end tests
All 104 tests are unit tests. No integration tests cover the API routes or the full auth flow.




Stats → Matchup Projection Screen — Design Assessment
Files: components/matchups/ProjectionCard.tsx, components/matchups/MatchupsClient.tsx, components/matchups/HistoryCard.tsx, components/matchups/PlayerPairSelector.tsx

High impact
A. ProjectionCard does too much in one card
The card combines: team framing, hero probability (64px), moneyline (40px), and 5 metric cells in a two-column layout. The two large stacked numbers (% and moneyline) compete visually. The win probability is the social hook and emotional centrepiece — it should be staged as a hero moment, not a data dump.
Recommendation: split into a Hero card (teams + % + moneyline) and a collapsible Details card (Δ Rating, Confidence, Volatility, Momentum, Expectation Gap). The hero card should span full width with the probability front and centre.

B. Team names are too quiet
Team names render at text-base (16px) in zinc-50/zinc-500. The matchup pairing is the entire premise of the screen but it's styled at body-copy weight. Sports apps treat the team matchup as the visual anchor — here it's an afterthought above the big numbers.
Recommendation: Larger, bolder team-vs-team presentation. Consider a split layout: "Ali / Sam" left-aligned, "Jordan / Chris" right-aligned, with the % bridging them. Or a probability bar spanning the two team names to show the 73/27 split visually.

C. No transition on selector collapse
The collapsible player selector snaps open/closed with no animation. The auto-collapse after all 4 players are selected is especially jarring — content disappears and results appear as a jump cut.
Recommendation: CSS max-height transition (200ms ease-out) on the expandable body. Low effort, high polish payoff.

Medium impact
D. Loading state is too bare
"Computing projection…" plain text appears after the selector collapses. The screen already knows all 4 player names at this point — it could show a skeleton card with team names pre-rendered and a pulsing placeholder where the % will appear.
Recommendation: Skeleton ProjectionCard that shows team names immediately and pulses the % / moneyline areas while the fetch completes.

E. Changing a player requires too many steps
Collapsed state shows "Ali / Sam vs Jordan / Chris" — to swap one player: expand → find ✕ → clear → search or pick chip again. For a quick "what if?" swap this is 4 interactions.
Recommendation: Tapping a player name in the collapsed summary could open just that slot for editing inline. Or show subtle per-name edit icons in the collapsed header.

F. HistoryCard has no emotional punch
Record "3–2 · Avg Margin +4.2" is a small-caps paragraph before a list of rows. Head-to-head record is psychologically meaningful — "you've won 5 in a row" is exciting — but the current treatment buries it.
Recommendation: Show the record as a prominent stat (larger, coloured) before the row list. Add a mini 5-dot win/loss streak indicator (green/red circles) for instant pattern recognition.

Lower impact
G. Empty state below selector is wasted space
Before any players are selected, the screen shows header + selector + blank space. First-time users have no preview of what they'll get.
Recommendation: A faint preview illustration of the result card or a 3-stat explainer (Win %, Moneyline, Momentum) in the empty area.

H. ShareButton and invite section are visually unrelated
Both are social actions but they render as separate blocks separated in the scroll order. The invite section ("Not on Vector yet") is easily missed.
Recommendation: Group Share + Invite into a single "Share & Invite" card after the ProjectionCard.



